Most of us start with TEST TEST TEST to gain a knowledge of food's
effects on us.

However, one of the valuable side effects of frequent testing for me has
been self-control. High numbers after problem foods make me want to do
better the next time.

On the other hand, I could see some people getting accustomed to high
numbers and getting desensitized to their meaning.

We know that frequent testing is associated with better blood glucose
control from research.

But what accounts for the better control: food knowledge or a developed
self-control resulting from alarming meter readings?

More likely it's a mix of both, but how much of the improvement is
self-control?

Can we depend on frequent testing to develop our self control?

Can we recommend it to others for this purpose?
