I think we can say for sure that without frequent testing--at least
when we are familiarizing ourselves with which foods do what--no self
control can be developed.  Without knowledge, achieving self control
is impossible.  For myself, now that I know which foods do what, I
don't deviate, so I rely more on spot-checking.  However, if I'm
trying a new food, I'm sure to test.

Other factors may come into play besides simple logic.  For myself, I
feel physically bad if I eat something that spikes my BG, but other
people may not experience this.  They have no immediate feedback
against eating a BG-spiking food other than logic--the number on their
meter.  I've also had the benefit of having worked in a hospital and
seeing the ravages that can be inflicted on uncontrolled diabetic
patients.  This gives me an emotional association in the form of fear
of to avoid BG-spiking foods.  Both of these points figure into my
personal self-control.  However, if a person does not have these or
other methods for maintaing self-control, the only other item s/he can
rely on is what the meter is saying.  In this case, I would definitely
recommend frequent testing.

Nothing is full-proof; people can always choose to not to alter their
lifestyles, but the meter at least gives us a means to attempt to
control our BGs.

Best regards,
